Juan Manuel Alvarez was convicted of causing a fatal train crash in Los Angeles.
Prosecutors claimed he did it for attention, while defense lawyers argued it was a failed suicide attempt.
The jury recommended life in prison without parole, not the death penalty.
Alvarez's troubled past, including abuse and mental illness, was highlighted in court.
Despite the tragic outcome, some believe he did not intend to harm others.
The emotional trial included testimony from relatives of the victims and Alvarez's own family, shedding light on the complex factors that led to the devastating incident.
